===Influence on live entertainment===
Felipe Branco Cruz from ''[[Veja (magazine)|Veja]]'' stated Coldplay "reinvented the concept of arena rock", as their live performances turned fans into the show's protagonists instead of mere spectators, consequently carrying on the legacy of spectacles "which transcend music" that was established by groups such as [[Pink Floyd]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and U2.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 September 2022 |title=Com Show no Rock in Rio, Coldplay Reinventa o Conceito de Rock de Arena |trans-title=With Rock in Rio Show, Coldplay Reinvents the Concept of Arena Rock |url=https://veja.abril.com.br/cultura/com-show-no-rock-in-rio-coldplay-reinventa-o-conceito-de-rock-de-arena/ |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220911111809/https://veja.abril.com.br/cultura/com-show-no-rock-in-rio-coldplay-reinventa-o-conceito-de-rock-de-arena/ |archive-date=11 September 2022 |access-date=11 September 2022 |website=Veja |language=pt }}</ref> The band are widely credited with popularizing the use of interactive [[Light-emitting diode|LED]] wristbands in concerts as well.<ref name="XYLOB" /> Acts who followed their trend include [[Lady Gaga]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 February 2017 |title=Lady Gaga's Show Featured Audience Lighting Effects Made Famous by Coldplay |url=https://www.newswire.com/news/super-bowl-half-time-lights-up-audience-with-led-effects-18752735 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220809112454/https://www.newswire.com/news/super-bowl-half-time-lights-up-audience-with-led-effects-18752735 |archive-date=9 August 2022 |access-date=9 August 2022 |website=Newswire}}</ref> Taylor Swift,<ref name="XYLOB" /> OneRepublic,<ref name="XYLOB" /> [[The Weeknd]],<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=15 July 2022 |title=The Weeknd Takes Us Inside His Brave New World – Finally – In Spectacular Stadium Tour Opener |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/weeknd-after-hours-til-dawn-tour-review-1383291/ |url-status=live |magazine=Rolling Stone |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220715174450/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/weeknd-after-hours-til-dawn-tour-review-1383291/ |archive-date=15 July 2022 |access-date=16 July 2022}}</ref> and [[Jay-Z]].<ref name="XYLOB" /> Jason Regler, the product's creator, said his idea was conceived during a Coldplay show.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 May 2012 |title=Interview: Xylobands Inventor Jason Regler |url=http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=906 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510172755/http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=906 |archive-date=10 May 2012 |access-date=18 May 2021 |website=Coldplay Official Website}}</ref> According to Didier Zacharie from ''[[Le Soir]]'', the ecological plan proposed by the [[Music of the Spheres World Tour]] (2022–23) was "unprecedented" for a stadium tour,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 August 2022 |title=La Tournée de Coldplay Est-Elle Vraiment Écologique? |trans-title=Is the Coldplay Tour Really Eco-friendly? |url=https://www.lesoir.be/457640/article/2022-08-02/la-tournee-de-coldplay-est-elle-vraiment-ecologique |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220804140948/https://www.lesoir.be/457640/article/2022-08-02/la-tournee-de-coldplay-est-elle-vraiment-ecologique |archive-date=4 August 2022 |access-date=5 August 2022 |website=Le Soir |language=fr }}</ref> leading the band to be credited with "laying down the blueprints" for environmentally friendly touring.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 September 2022 |title=Music of the Spheres – The Tour Report |url=https://www.iq-mag.net/2022/09/music-of-the-spheres-the-tour-report/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220919181407/https://www.iq-mag.net/2022/09/music-of-the-spheres-the-tour-report/ |archive-date=19 September 2022 |access-date=19 September 2022 |website=IQ}}</ref> In 2022, [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]]'s Lucy August-Perna commented they helped to further build on the framework the company had been developing during the previous five years and their best practices and plans will be standardized to "provide sustainable touring options" for more artists.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=22 April 2022 |title=Touring Returned From The Pandemic Greener Than Ever |url=https://www.billboard.com/pro/concerts-green-touring-pandemic-coldplay-billie-eilish/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220426221638/https://www.billboard.com/pro/concerts-green-touring-pandemic-coldplay-billie-eilish/ |archive-date=26 April 2022 |access-date=26 April 2022 |magazine=Billboard}}</ref> ''[[Uproxx]]'' and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' recognized Coldplay's impact on Billie Eilish's [[Happier Than Ever, The World Tour]] and [[Shawn Mendes]]' [[Wonder: The World Tour]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=29 April 2022 |title=Shawn Mendes Announces Sustainability Initiatives For Wonder Tour |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/shawn-mendes-sustainability-initiatives-wonder-tour-exclusive-1235064810/ |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220627180457/https://www.billboard.com/music/pop/shawn-mendes-sustainability-initiatives-wonder-tour-exclusive-1235064810/ |archive-date=27 June 2022 |access-date=27 June 2022 |magazine=Billboard }}
* {{Cite web |date=7 June 2022 |title=From Coldplay To Billie Eilish, Summer Tours Are Putting A Focus On Sustainability |url=https://uproxx.com/music/summer-tour-sustainability-coldplay-shawn-mendes-billie-eilish/ |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220627180830/https://uproxx.com/music/summer-tour-sustainability-coldplay-shawn-mendes-billie-eilish/ |archive-date=27 June 2022 |access-date=27 June 2022 |website=Uproxx }}</ref> Their work in partnership with John Wiseman (from Worldwide Sales) and Frederic Opsomer (from PRG Projects) for the stage's LED elements resulted in the creation of products "that never existed before", such as inflatable three-dimensional orbs which "dramatically" reduced the necessary space to store and transport regular models.<ref name="PRGREF">{{Cite web |date=27 July 2022 |title=Executive Profile: PRG Lights Up Coldplay's Music of the Spheres Stadium Tour |url=https://news.pollstar.com/2022/07/27/executive-profile-prg-lights-up-coldplays-music-of-the-spheres-stadium-tour/ |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730155034/https://news.pollstar.com/2022/07/27/executive-profile-prg-lights-up-coldplays-music-of-the-spheres-stadium-tour/ |archive-date=30 July 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022 |website=Pollstar }}</ref> Opsomer also said the custom technology developed for the tour will become "commonplace in a few years" in the live entertainment industry, thanking the band for "having the vision and backbone" of the endeavour.<ref name="PRGREF" />

==Other activities==
===Philanthropy===
Coldplay donates 10 percent from all of their profits to charity.<ref>{{cite news|date=5 May 2005|title=Coldplay's Slow-burning Success|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2780109.stm|access-date=29 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805124727/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2780109.stm|archive-date=5 August 2019}}
* {{Cite web|date=14 October 2021|title=ClientEarth Reaction: Coldplay Announce Music of the Spheres Word Tour|url=https://www.clientearth.org/latest/press-office/press/coldplay-world-tour-release/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229134028/https://www.clientearth.org/latest/press-office/press/coldplay-world-tour-release/|archive-date=29 December 2021|access-date=16 January 2022|website=Client Earth}}</ref> The fund is held in a bank account none of the members can access.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 January 2003|title=Coldplay To Donate 10th of Earnings To Charity|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/arid-30082906.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229134029/https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/arid-30082906.html|archive-date=29 December 2021|access-date=16 January 2022|website=Irish Examiner}}</ref> The band currently endorses over thirty organizations,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Coldplay: Charity Work & Causes|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/celebrity/coldplay|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116231501/https://www.looktothestars.org/celebrity/coldplay|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=18 May 2021|website=Look to the Stars}}</ref> including [[Amnesty International]], [[Migrant Offshore Aid Station]] and [[Global Citizen Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=17 March 2017|title=Coldplay Brings 20 Years of Music and Charity to Global Citizen Germany|url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/coldplay-global-citizen-festival-hamburg/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116231525/https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/coldplay-global-citizen-festival-hamburg/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=Global Citizen}}</ref> They have been vocal about [[fair trade]], supporting [[Oxfam]]'s [[Make Trade Fair]] campaign by collecting over 70,000 signatures for their "Big Noise" petition at [[A Rush of Blood to the Head Tour]] and [[Twisted Logic Tour]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=23 March 2006|title=During Second Leg of US Tour, Coldplay Campaigns To Make Trade Fair|url=https://www.oxfamamerica.org/explore/stories/during-second-leg-of-us-tour-coldplay-campaigns-to-make-trade-fair/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116231631/https://www.oxfamamerica.org/explore/stories/during-second-leg-of-us-tour-coldplay-campaigns-to-make-trade-fair/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=Oxfam America}}</ref> In 2005, they partnered with the [[Make Poverty History]] movement and appeared on their campaigns.<ref>{{Cite web|date=6 September 2014|title=What happened to the Make Poverty History movement?|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/what-happened-to-the-make-poverty-history-movement-20140905-10ciar.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116231748/https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/what-happened-to-the-make-poverty-history-movement-20140905-10ciar.html|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> Coldplay also auctioned many significant memorabilia in 2009 for [[Kids Company]], including Martin's first guitar, the globe from the ''[[Parachutes (Coldplay album)|Parachutes]]'' (2000) album cover and the costumes worn during [[Viva la Vida Tour]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coldplay's Chris Martin to Auction His First Guitar for Charity |work=NME |url=https://www.nme.com/news/coldplay/48938 |access-date=29 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220013619/https://www.nme.com/news/coldplay/48938 |archive-date=20 December 2009}}</ref> In the following year, they became patrons for [[ClientEarth]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 November 2010 |title=Coldplay Become Patrons of ClientEarth |url=http://coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=665 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174633/http://coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=665 |archive-date=8 July 2011 |access-date=3 June 2022 |website=Coldplay Official Website}}</ref>

[[File:Coldplay Twisted Logic Live 2006 in Singapore Indoor Stadium.jpg|thumb|[[Make Trade Fair]], abbreviated as MTF, shown on Martin's piano|alt=Make Trade Fair shown on Chris Martin's piano.]]
The band performed a slightly modified version of "A Message", entitled "A Message 2010", at the [[Hope for Haiti Now|Hope For Haiti Now]] telethon special, raising money for the victims of the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hope For Haiti Now Concert YouTube Broadcast Info|work=Coldplay Official Website|url=http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=577|url-status=dead|access-date=29 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124081110/http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=577|archive-date=24 January 2010}}</ref> Berryman commented that "You can make people aware of issues. It isn't very much effort for us at all, if it can help people, then we want to do it".<ref name="Roach 78">{{harv|Roach|2003|p=78}}</ref> In 2012, Album Artists staged an exhibition made up of artwork from ''[[Mylo Xyloto]]'' (2011) in [[Camden Town|Camden]], it raised over £610,000 for Kids Company.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=275647685195866113|user=coldplay|title=Take a bow Coldplay fans. An incredible £610,000 raised so far from the Mylo art sale @AlbumArtists @KidsCo_Tweets. PH|author=Coldplay|date=3 December 2012|access-date=16 January 2022|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130615182704/https://twitter.com/coldplay/status/275647685195866113|archive-date=15 June 2013|url-status=live|website=Twitter}}</ref> Two years later, Martin joined charity group [[Band Aid (band)|Band Aid]] for a second time, performing alongside British and Irish acts on a new version of "[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]" that raised money for the [[2014 Ebola outbreaks|Ebola crisis]] in [[West Africa|Western Africa]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=10 November 2014|title=Band Aid 30: One Direction Among Celebrity Line-up|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|access-date=8 December 2015|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html|archive-date=10 January 2022}}</ref> In July 2017, the band made a donation of undisclosed value for [[University of Southampton]]'s Centre for Cancer Immunology, which is the United Kingdom's first centre dedicated to cancer immunology research.<ref>{{Cite web|date=19 July 2017|title=Coldplay Support University Cancer Campaign|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2017/07/coldplay-cic-donation.page|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220201062549/https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2017/07/coldplay-cic-donation.page|archive-date=1 February 2022|access-date=1 February 2022|website=University of Southampton}}</ref>

Coldplay have also contributed to the ''Plastic Oceans Album'' by [[Artists' Project Earth]], the record was released on 20 February 2018 at the Ocean Plastics Crisis Summit in London, raising awareness and funds to counter [[plastic pollution]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Artists Project Earth – Description|url=https://oceanconference.un.org/commitments/?id=15302|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503180112/https://oceanconference.un.org/commitments/?id=15302|archive-date=3 May 2017|access-date=29 December 2021|website=The Ocean Conference}}</ref> Under the pseudonym Los Unidades, the band made ''[[Global Citizen – EP 1]]'' available on the same year, with royalties being directed to the organization's efforts of education and advocacy towards the end of [[extreme poverty]].<ref>{{cite web|date=30 November 2018|title=Stream Coldplay's New Collaborative EP as Los Unidades|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/11/coldplay-los-unidades-global-citizen-ep-1-listen/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190213202742/https://www.spin.com/2018/11/coldplay-los-unidades-global-citizen-ep-1-listen/|archive-date=13 February 2019|access-date=16 January 2022|website=Spin}}</ref> In 2020, they released a music video for "Trouble In Town", inspired by [[George Orwell]]'s ''[[Animal Farm]]'' (1944), and donated all proceeds from streaming and publishing to the [[Innocence Project]] and the African Children's Feeding Scheme.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=12 March 2020|title=Coldplay bring Animal Farm to the present on Trouble In Town video|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/coldplay-trouble-in-town-video-966121/|url-status=live|magazine=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116232423/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/coldplay-trouble-in-town-video-966121/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021}}</ref> Coldplay declared support to [[The Ocean Cleanup]] project as well, sponsoring two watercrafts that collect plastic from polluted rivers before it reaches the sea in [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 March 2021 |title=Coldplay Sponsors Watercraft To Clean Up Polluted Rivers In Malaysia |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/coldplay-sponsors-watercraft-to-clean-up-polluted-rivers-in-malaysia-2910867 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116232457/https://www.nme.com/news/music/coldplay-sponsors-watercraft-to-clean-up-polluted-rivers-in-malaysia-2910867 |archive-date=16 January 2022 |access-date=29 December 2021 |website=NME}}</ref> As part of the band's efforts to make touring more sustainable, they announced a partnership with One Tree Planted, funding a tree for every ticket sold at [[Music of the Spheres World Tour]] through a global reforestation agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 October 2021 |title=One Tree Planted To Fulfill Coldplay's Reforestation Targets Around Music of the Spheres World Tour |url=https://onetreeplanted.org/blogs/stories/coldplay-sustainability-reforestation |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116232615/https://onetreeplanted.org/blogs/stories/coldplay-sustainability-reforestation |archive-date=16 January 2022 |access-date=29 December 2021 |website=One Tree Planted}}</ref> According to a report published by ''[[The Times]]'', they donated over £2.1 million to environmental causes through their J Van Mars Foundation during 2021.<ref name="RICH" />

===Politics and activism===
[[File:Believe In Love (Super Bowl 50).png|thumb|The ending of Coldplay's [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]] performance|alt=Super Bowl 50 halftime show ending.]]
Martin, who lives in the United States, spoke out against the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] led by country along with other military forces during a [[Teenage Cancer Trust]] concert at [[London]]'s [[Royal Albert Hall]], encouraging the sold-out venue's crowd to "sing against war".<ref>{{Cite web|date=23 March 2003|title=Liam Gallagher Slams Chris Martin's Anti-war Stance|url=https://www.nme.com/news/oasis/13953|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091116175347/https://www.nme.com/news/oasis/13953|archive-date=16 November 2009|access-date=29 December 2021|website=NME}}</ref> He also showed support for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential candidates [[John Kerry]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite news|date=9 February 2004|title=Kerry, On A Roll|work=CNN|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/02/09/mgrind.day.mon/|access-date=29 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818013844/http://edition.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/02/09/mgrind.day.mon/|archive-date=18 August 2011}}</ref> and [[Barack Obama]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|date=29 January 2009|title=Chris Martin Shows Obama Support|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/chris-martin-shows-obama-support|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203092945/https://www.clashmusic.com/news/chris-martin-shows-obama-support|archive-date=3 February 2009|access-date=29 December 2021|work=Clash}}</ref> One year later, the band started to take part in [[Meatless Monday|Meat Free Mondays]], a food campaign started by [[Paul McCartney]] which attempts to help slow climate change by having at least one meat free day a week.<ref>{{cite web|date=18 June 2009|title=Coldplay back Meat Free Monday|url=http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=426&page=0|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620194605/http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=426&page=0|archive-date=20 June 2009|access-date=29 December 2021|website=Coldplay Official Website}}</ref> In 2011, Coldplay endorsed the song "[[Freedom for Palestine]]" by posting a link to the music video on their social media, they received over 12,000 comments in less than day, with fans either agreeing or disagreeing with the message. Some threatened to boycott them and created a group that demanded an apology to [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite news|date=3 June 2011|title=Coldplay Angers Fans by Telling Them to Check Out Freedom For Palestine Video|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/blogpost/post/coldplay-angers-fans-by-telling-them-to-check-out-freedom-for-palestine-video/2011/06/03/AG50OvHH_blog.html|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105190912/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/blogpost/post/coldplay-angers-fans-by-telling-them-to-check-out-freedom-for-palestine-video/2011/06/03/AG50OvHH_blog.html|archive-date=5 November 2015}}</ref> Eventually the post was deleted from their pages, however, [[Frank Barat]] of OneWorld stated it was actually removed by [[Facebook]] after "thousands of people and computer generated posts reported it as abusive", rather than the band's management.<ref>{{Cite web|date=9 June 2011|title=Palestine Campaign Song Generates Controversy Ahead of Release|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/view-from-jerusalem-with-harriet-sherwood/2011/jun/09/palestinian-territories-gaza|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116233139/https://www.theguardian.com/world/view-from-jerusalem-with-harriet-sherwood/2011/jun/09/palestinian-territories-gaza|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=The Guardian}}</ref>

Coldplay have advocated for the [[LGBT community|LGBTQ community]] as well, sparking controversy with their performance at the [[Super Bowl 50 halftime show]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=8 February 2016|title=Football Fans Are Outraged by the Super Bowl's Gay Agenda|url=https://archive.attn.com/|url-status=dead|access-date=29 December 2021|website=ATTN|archive-date=18 November 2018|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20181118214029/https://www.attn.com/}}</ref> The band were accused of promoting the "[[gay agenda]]" by [[Conservatism in the United States|conservatives]] for the show's last moment,<ref>{{Cite web|date=8 February 2016|title=Coldplay & Beyoncé Accused of Gay Propaganda in Last Night's Super Bowl Halftime Show|url=https://www.dailydot.com/irl/super-bowl-halftime-gay-propaganda/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116233516/https://www.dailydot.com/irl/super-bowl-halftime-gay-propaganda/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=The Daily Dot}}</ref> where the audience flipped over rainbow-colored placards that read "Believe In Love".<ref>{{Cite web|first=|date=8 February 2016|title=Super Bowl 50's Pro-Gay Marriage Moment Sends A Beautiful Message About Love|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/140337-super-bowl-50s-pro-gay-marriage-moment-sends-a-beautiful-message-about-love|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116233539/https://www.bustle.com/articles/140337-super-bowl-50s-pro-gay-marriage-moment-sends-a-beautiful-message-about-love|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=Bustle}}</ref> They are also among the artists that signed a public letter supporting the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]] in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Artist Letter in Support of the Equality Act|url=https://theallycoalition.org/equality-act/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116233657/https://theallycoalition.org/equality-act/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=The Ally Coalition}}</ref> In June 2016, Coldplay were in favour of "Vote Remain" at the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]]. Following the [[Brexit]] result, which saw 52% of the country voting to leave the European Union despite the majority of younger people voting to remain, Martin commented that "This decision does not represent us or indeed most of our generation and the generation following us".<ref>{{cite web|date=28 July 2016|title=Coldplay's Chris Martin Appeals For Unity After Brexit|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a799058/coldplay-chris-martin-appeals-for-unity-after-brexit/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116233730/https://www.digitalspy.com/music/a799058/coldplay-chris-martin-appeals-for-unity-after-brexit/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=Digital Spy}}</ref> A year later, they performed at [[Ariana Grande]]'s [[One Love Manchester]] benefit concert, which was organized in response to the [[Manchester Arena bombing]] and raised funds to help victims of the attack, as well as their families.<ref>{{cite news|date=30 May 2017|title=Ariana Grande's Manchester Benefit Concert to Air Live on BBC One|work=Evening Standard|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/ariana-grande-s-manchester-benefit-concert-to-air-live-on-bbc-one-a3552716.html|url-status=live|access-date=29 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613201342/http://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/ariana-grande-s-manchester-benefit-concert-to-air-live-on-bbc-one-a3552716.html|archive-date=13 June 2017}}</ref> Months later, they performed as special guests at the [[A Concert for Charlottesville|Concert for Charlottesville]] following the events of the [[Unite the Right rally]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=25 September 2017|title=A Concert for Charlottesville: Thousands Pack Stadium for Unity Concert|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2017/09/25/thousands-pack-charlottesville-stadium-for-unity-concert/105976476/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220116234136/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2017/09/25/thousands-pack-charlottesville-stadium-for-unity-concert/105976476/|archive-date=16 January 2022|access-date=29 December 2021|website=USA Today}}</ref> In November 2019, the band released ''[[Everyday Life (Coldplay album)|Everyday Life]]'', which saw them voicing more prominently their stance against [[racism]], [[police brutality]] and [[gun violence]].<ref name="DFTB" />

===Endorsements===
Despite their worldwide popularity, Coldplay have remained notoriously protective of how their material appears in the media.<ref name="SMLT">{{Cite web |date=1 March 2012 |title=Top 5 Things You May Not Know About Coldplay |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/03/top-5-things-you-may-not-know-about-coldplay |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106210922/https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/03/top-5-things-you-may-not-know-about-coldplay |archive-date=6 January 2022 |access-date=19 August 2021 |website=ABC News}}</ref> The band allow songs to be used in movies and television shows regularly, but commercials are limited to very rare occasions.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 2003 |title=Countdown For Clocks |url=http://www.coldplay.com/ezine/ezine8.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050514210230/http://www.coldplay.com/ezine/ezine8.pdf |archive-date=14 May 2005 |access-date=13 June 2022 |website=Coldplay E-Zine}}</ref> In 2002, it was reported they turned down over $85 million in contracts from companies such as [[Gatorade]], [[Diet Coke]] and [[Gap Inc.|Gap]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=24 August 2002|title=No Trouble For Adverts|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/coldplay-615-1381235|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106211612/https://www.nme.com/news/music/coldplay-615-1381235|archive-date=6 January 2022|access-date=6 January 2022|website=NME}}</ref> Martin said "We would not be able to live with ourselves if we sold the songs' meanings like that".<ref name="SMLT" /> The first instance one of their songs were used for advertisements was with "[[Viva la Vida]]" in 2008, the band signed a deal with [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and promoted the single's exclusive availability on [[iTunes Store|iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|date=21 May 2008|title=Coldplay iTunes Ad Debuts on US TV|url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1034284|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120526061201/http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=1034284|archive-date=26 May 2012|access-date=6 January 2022|work=Music Week}}</ref> In 2010, Martin appeared at the company's September event.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 September 2010|title=Apple Special Event September 2010|url=https://www.apple.com/apple-events/september-2010/|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903202039/http://www.apple.com/apple-events/september-2010/|archive-date=3 September 2010|access-date=28 December 2021|work=Apple Inc}}</ref> After the death of [[Steve Jobs]], Coldplay performed four tracks at the [[Apple Campus]], posthumously thanking his support.<ref>{{cite web|date=24 October 2011|title=Watch The October 19th, 2011 Apple Event Celebrating Steve Jobs|url=https://tidbits.com/2011/10/24/watch-the-19-october-2011-apple-event-celebrating-steve-jobs/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211201222118/https://tidbits.com/2011/10/24/watch-the-19-october-2011-apple-event-celebrating-steve-jobs/|archive-date=1 December 2021|access-date=6 January 2022|website=TidBits}}</ref>

[[File:A_Sky_Full_of_Stars_Target_AD_(2014).png|thumb|[[Target Corporation|Target]] commercial where Coldplay promoted ''[[Ghost Stories (Coldplay album)|Ghost Stories]]'' (2014)|alt=Coldplay's Target commercial in 2014.]]
Six years later, they took part in a [[Target Corporation|Target]] commercial which promoted the exclusive deluxe edition of ''[[Ghost Stories (Coldplay album)|Ghost Stories]]'' (2014).<ref>{{Cite web|date=5 May 2014|title=There's a Sky Full of (Paper) Stars in Coldplay's Target Commercial|url=http://corporate.target.com/article/2014/05/theres-a-sky-full-of-paper-stars-in-coldplays-targ|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106213802/https://corporate.target.com/article/2014/05/theres-a-sky-full-of-paper-stars-in-coldplays-targ|archive-date=6 January 2022|access-date=11 June 2021|website=Target}}</ref> Meanwhile, the music video for "[[Adventure of a Lifetime]]", which was directed by [[Mat Whitecross]] and recorded at [[The Imaginarium]], had a [[Beats Electronics|Beats]] product placement.<ref>{{Cite web|date=10 March 2016|title=Bands & Brands: The New Music Business|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/bands-brands-new-music-business/1386597|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106214130/https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/bands-brands-new-music-business/1386597|archive-date=6 January 2022|access-date=6 January 2022|website=Campaign}}</ref> The company was allowed to use some parts of the video on their commercials as a return for covering the budget. In 2018, director [[Jon M. Chu]] revealed he sent a letter directly to the band laying out all his reasons in order to get a permission for using "[[Yellow (Coldplay song)|Yellow]]" on ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|date=19 August 2018|title=Crazy Rich Asians: Read the Letter That Convinced Coldplay to Allow Yellow in the Movie|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/general-news/read-crazy-rich-asians-director-s-letter-coldplay-yellow-1135826/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106210409/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/general-news/read-crazy-rich-asians-director-s-letter-coldplay-yellow-1135826/|archive-date=6 January 2022|access-date=6 January 2022|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> After it was granted, a Chinese-language cover of the track was commissioned as well.

In 2021, Coldplay announced a major partnership with German multinational [[BMW]] as part of their efforts to make touring as sustainable as possible.<ref name="BMWHP">{{Cite web|date=11 June 2021|title=The First-ever BMW iX and the First-ever BMW i4: Joint Global Campaign Plays to the Rhythm of Coldplay's New Hit|url=https://www.press.bmwgroup.com/global/article/detail/T0335298EN/the-first-ever-bmw-ix-and-the-first-ever-bmw-i4:-joint-global-campaign-plays-to-the-rhythm-of-coldplay-s-new-hit?language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106225032/https://www.press.bmwgroup.com/global/article/detail/T0335298EN/the-first-ever-bmw-ix-and-the-first-ever-bmw-i4:-joint-global-campaign-plays-to-the-rhythm-of-coldplay-s-new-hit?language=en|archive-date=6 January 2022|access-date=13 June 2021|website=Press BMW Group}}</ref> They elaborated by commenting on how the company's technology, which includes the first recyclable car batteries in the world, is able to power live performances almost entirely from renewable energy. Their shows then incorporated solar installations, a kinetic floor in each venue and generators powered by hydrotreated vegetable oil.<ref>{{Cite web|date=18 December 2021|title=Coldplay's New Tour Powered by BMW Batteries|url=https://luxuryboutiquemagazine.com/2021/10/18/coldplays-new-tour-powered-by-bmw-batteries/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220106230929/https://luxuryboutiquemagazine.com/2021/10/18/coldplays-new-tour-powered-by-bmw-batteries/|archive-date=6 January 2022|access-date=6 January 2022|website=Luxury Boutique}}</ref> As part of the deal, the band contributed creatively on the marketing campaign of two electric cars from the company and allowed "[[Higher Power (song)|Higher Power]]" to be used in television advertisements.<ref name="BMWHP" />

